<br>
It is a recognized right in this country to have reproductive freedom.  It has been argued before the supreme court and the court supported the individual's rights to choose to reproduce.  The particular law requiring those on welfare to have mandatory temporary sterilization ( read noroplant for females ) was struck down by the Supreme Court as unconstitutional and an infringement on basic human rights.  <br>
<br>
Again this issue is not so much the scarves, or burka, yes there is a religious issue but there are non religious issues as well.  Are the schools going to tell a child going through chemotherapy they cannot wear a scarf or hat to hide the side effects of radiation treatments.  There is more than a religious reason to wear a scarf to school.  The covering of the head in the muslim religion is a submission to modesty because in the Koran a woman's hair is her highest glory and should only be exposed to her husband or close family members.  The burka is a far more extreme version of the scarf and has been turned into a symbol of supression of women's rights, but in reality and under the religion it is simply a mandated modesty.  Do musslem women support this, I honestly don't know, I do know what the Koran says and that the scarf is considered a symbol of muslim faith by women.  Should children be forced to wear them that is a parental issue, simply because RELIGION for young children is a parental issue.  To mandate either that a child be forced to follow a religion or forced NOT to follow a religion is not the state's place to say.  In children who are older and able to make their own choices, if they choose to follow the religious mandates of their chosen religion they should have that right.  Should they be able to force those beliefs on others NO but should they be mandated NOT to follow their religious teaching on public property I don't know.  I think that if it creates a distraction in school or creates a situation that is dangerous than that might be a cause to restrict certain rights within reason.  The key is WITHIN REASON.  There are public schools that are experimenting with uniforms for all students and if that is the way it goes then I am not against that because it creates a better learning environment for the students, but it needs to apply to ALL students, not just limit the rights of certain groups.  And it should be worded in such a way that it infringes on the rights of any groups, but in such a way that it mandates behavior for all without bias.  That is a major issue, uniformity if it is going to be enforced should be done uniformly and without bias.<br>
 <p>Kelley<br>
