<br>
Ykrobe and I have talked before about other issues relating to French politics. He bangs around here, and it is a good thing. We should discuss these issues. We should talk about what we think is important and why Americans believe what we do. I think there are a lot of things we can teach the world about lassez-faire (zut!) captialism, and we could learn a lot from our friends overseas.<br>
<br>
We may disagree about some issues, however, in France, there is a influx of people from North Africa who are not wanting anything from France but a hand out. They are not immigrants like here. They are refugees. One problem has been due to the revolving door at the border. <br>
<br>
This is a anti-fundimentalist law, the head scarves are NOT a religeous message but a political one, in the opinion of many French people. We find banning a religeous symbol repugnant, and in the US, we assume that someone here wants to live here. From a French perspective, Arabs dont want to be in France but can't return to North Africa.<br>
<br>
I would counter this way, people should be permitted to live and wear, what they wish, but I would have dismantled the socialist system of free breakfast, lunch, and dinner. There would be few Muslim refugees in France because they would have moved to Germany to get a free hand out there.<br>
