<br>
Euros...you have yer beliefs and that's fine.  You won't find a lot of Americans here that will agree with them, even if they DON'T like Bush.  Taking cheap potshots at the people that are actually over there doing the dirty work, though, is just flat out wrong.  Yer disrespecting men and women that went over there because it's their job.  The US military has a lot of excellent opportunities for young people.  Free college while serving, a big chunck of cash for college after you get out.  A lot of jobs offer skills that are highly desired in the civilian sector (electrical engineering, satellite communications, medical, etc).  It's a good place to go after high school.  Some people actually enjoy it so much that they stay in.  Some get out as soon as they can.  It all depends on the person.<br>
<br>
This time of year, even the most &quot;gung-ho&quot;  and die hard soldier questions their career descions.  In a hostile country, in harm's way, defending a people that you can't trust.  Sure they can get out when their contracts expire.  Some can risk going to jail and just leave now.  No honor in that, of course.  Yes they knew the risk of war, at home or elsewhere, when they joined.<br>
<br>
Regardless, they are there...whether they like it or not, fighting and dying and doing the best they can do for people they can't trust.  <br>
<br>
Say what you want about my government...but damn it - don't trash them!!!  They are doing what they have to do and if you ask any one of them - their answer will be along the lines of &quot;we're here to HELP&quot;.<br>
<br>
Americans - Picking on the Euros because of how they communicate is a desperate dig for footing.  Trust me, I had many nasty arguements with the likes of Yk and Estephe and Passe.  They won't change their opinions.  You, also, won't change yours.<br>
<br>
We all get different news.  Euros get their news from different souces then Americans do.  Yes, I can honestly say that American news is VERY biased.  I've also noticed news from European sources to be slanted.  The best way to get the MOST of the story as you can is to look at all the sources you can and pick out the similarities.  <br>
<br>
I'm all for liberating the Iraqi people, rebuilding the country, teaching them self-rule, and the sacrifice we are making.  I am all for saying &quot;No contracts and zero American dollars to countries that do not send troops to help stabilize Iraq&quot;.  I am all for the US telling the UN to take a seat on the sideline due to 13 years of inaction.<br>
<br>
Maybe we went about it wrong.  Maybe we could have handled it better.  But that's over.  We're there, the deed is done.  <br>
<br>
Where do we go from here? <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://pages.sbcglobal.net/youdaho/drack.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
